{:itonami.blueprint/id "cloud-itonami-3313"
 :itonami.blueprint/name "Community Electronic and Optical Equipment Repair Operations"
 :itonami.blueprint/isic-rev5 "3313"
 :itonami.blueprint/domain :manufacturing/electronic-equipment-repair
 :itonami.blueprint/license "AGPL-3.0-or-later"
 :itonami.blueprint/social-impact [:right-to-repair :waste-reduction :local-jobs]
 :itonami.blueprint/governor :electronic-repair-governor
 :itonami.blueprint/robotics true
 :itonami.blueprint/required-technologies [:robotics :identity :forms :dmn :bpmn :audit-ledger :eda :cae]
 :itonami.blueprint/optional-technologies []
 :itonami.blueprint/status :public-oss
 :itonami.blueprint/maturity :implemented
 :itonami.blueprint/implemented-slice
 "ElectronicRepairOps-LLM Advisor ⊣ Electronic Repair Governor,
 langgraph-clj StateGraph (langgraph.graph,
 electronicrepair.operation/build), append-only audit ledger
 (electronicrepair.store/ledger + append-ledger!, mem-store). Fixes a
 prior gap: `electronicrepair.operation` used to be four proposal-shape
 builder functions plus prose describing a \"PROPOSAL API\" -- it never
 `require`d `langgraph.graph`, never called
 state-graph/add-node/compile-graph, and was never itself required by
 anything else in `src/`. There was no `advisor.cljc`/`defprotocol`/mock
 ANYWHERE in this repo (only prose mentions of \"advise\" elsewhere; the
 four proposal functions were literal dead code, never run against the
 governor from any real flow). Now: a genuinely compiled StateGraph
 (`:intake -> :advise -> :govern -> :decide -+-> :commit /
 :request-approval -> :commit / :hold`) with `interrupt-before
 #{:request-approval}` + an in-memory checkpointer for real
 human-in-the-loop resume, mirroring `pastaops.operation`
 (cloud-itonami-isic-1074) node/edge structure. `electronicrepair.advisor`
 is a real `Advisor` protocol + `MockAdvisor` (new), with an op
 vocabulary derived directly from what `electronicrepair.governor/check`
 actually validates -- including a fifth op, `:complete-repair`
 (technician-completion sign-off LOGGING, never the hands-on repair
 itself), that governor already independently checked for
 (`already-completed-violations`, `:actuation/complete-repair`
 high-stakes) but had no proposal builder anywhere. Fixing this also
 surfaced and corrected a real gap in the moved proposal builders: the
 original `schedule-technician-dispatch` / `order-parts` never carried
 `:client-id`/`:equipment-id` in their `:value`, even though governor's
 `client-verification-violations`/`equipment-registration-violations`
 apply to those two ops as well as intake creation -- meaning every
 dispatch/parts-order proposal would have hard-held unconditionally the
 first time it was ever actually run through the governor (confirmed
 empirically pre-fix). `electronicrepair.store` now also exposes a
 `Store` protocol (`MemStore`) alongside its original pure value helpers
 (unchanged, still used directly by `electronicrepair.governor`'s
 independent checks). `:complete-repair` (real technician sign-off) and
 `:flag-safety-concern` (safety escalation) ALWAYS escalate to a human
 shop dispatcher via the compiled graph's `:request-approval` node
 (checkpoint-based resume), matching governor's own `high-stakes` set.
 Proven end-to-end by `test/electronicrepair/operation_graph_test.clj`
 exercising commit / hard-hold (unverified client) / escalate-approve /
 escalate-reject / duplicate-dispatch hard-hold (after a genuine prior
 commit) through the REAL compiled graph, including a falsifiable proof
 that a custom injected Advisor's own (randomly generated, non-hardcoded)
 proposal `:notes` is what lands in the committed ledger fact -- not a
 graph-internal literal -- and that `store/mark-completed!`/
 `mark-dispatched!` only fire as a genuine effect of a real `:commit`,
 never while merely interrupted awaiting approval. `deps.edn`'s dependency
 wiring (top-level `io.github.kotoba-lang/langgraph`) was already correct
 and is unchanged; `sim.cljc` (new) fills a real gap -- `deps.edn`'s `:run`
 alias already pointed at `-m electronicrepair.sim`, but that namespace
 did not exist anywhere in the repo before this fix."}
